div.div:
A diamond could be overlapping with shapes having a similar size (all three shapes) or edges (circle) or shape (triangle, square) or state (such as rotation state of a square) in such a way that if the shapes are aligned properly, the triangle could cover the other shapes, which is an example of a simple 'ambiguity resolution' using 'overlaps' and 'alignments' and 'similarities'.
That's three interface structures (overlap in center/side/corners, alignment in position/angle, similarity in size/shape/state) applied to solve the problem (after applying overlaps/alignments/similarities, what other shapes could be covered by the diamond?)
Core shapes can be tried first, but as an alternative, probable shapes can be generated, by applying combinations of similarities/differences to create overlaps/alignments/other relevant similarities that could create 'coverage', given that a similarity in size or a similarity in shape could create a possible coverage interaction between shapes.
This is an ambiguity resolution in that structures that appear falsely similar to another structure explain ambiguities. Another way to resolve ambiguities, when they result from 'lack of relevant differentiating variables', is to identify missing variables, rather than applying 'frequently differentiating variables (like changing angle or rotating)' by default.
So identifying 'all the structures that a particular structure can falsely seem like with adjacent changes or possible changes' is useful to identify, to recognize changes that could differentiate these structures from the actual structures they seem like (from different angles - a spiral seems like a circle, a rectangle seems like a square, etc - though these ambiguity-resolving change types don't work in reverse all the time).

div.div: For example, recursion is a complexity structure that is clarified when identifying vectors required for it to work (other than the halting condition and the function logic that makes progress toward it, the 're-direction/bubbling vector that bubbles up the output to the right position so that its output by the original function' is useful to identify as well, as this is the 'offsetting/different/opposite' structure of the 'recursion' structure which re-applies itself within itself like a fractal or iteration/sequence/stack, but the 'recursion' structure isn't the goal but rather a 'means to identify some value after iterating some process', so the 'recursion' structure should have an 'opposing' structure of a 'bubbling/re-direction vector', even if it just returns a value, bc a common error in recursion functions is not 're-directing/bubbling return values correctly', other than errors like 'not making progress toward halt condition' or 'not defining halt condition so that its always reached'. In other words, the problem is 'once you have this stack/sequence of function calls, how do you re-direct/bubble the final output back to the original, by offsetting this stack structure, so that the calling function of the original function call can receive its expected return value'.

div.div:
By contrast, a 'false simplicity' structure would be where a problem is 'over-simplified to a false degree', such as where resolving 'whether some variable occurs as a cause or effect of another variable' (resolving the position in the causal sequence of a variable set).
In reality, many other structures could falsely look like a 'simple, one-way causal connection'.
For example, a cyclical connection between the variables could occur, where if one segment of the cycle is observed, it could falsely look like a one-way causal connection'.
Similarly, a 'connection that can change/reverse its direction as needed' could falsely look like a 'simple one-way connection' if only one of the two direction options is observed.
Similarly, a 'connection with multiple alternate connections between variables' could falsely look like a 'simple one-way connection.
Similarly, a 'connection between two values of the same variable' could falsely look like 'two different variables'.
